result.execSummary:
The defendant Rachel M. Pries was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting/Failing to Stop/Fleeing, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(2t).
  • Resisting an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.  This applies to all counts and financial obligations.

Obey all of the rules and regulations of supervising probation agent.  Pay supervision fees.  Do not possess or consume alcoholic beverages and do not have alcoholic beverages within the residence.  Do not be in taverns or on any premises licensed for the sale of intoxicating beverages, except restaurants or grocery stores.  Do not possess or consume controlled substances, except by prescription.  Submit voluntarily to random tests of blood, breath or urine.  Participate in counseling deemed appropriate by your agent, which may include: alcohol/drug, anger management/DV counseling, psychiatric/psychological, AODA Assessment and follow-through with recommended treatment.  Actively search for employment, be employed or attend an educational institution or vocational training program.
*   Pay fine of $100 and court costs including all applicable surcharges.
*   If unpaid financial obligations remain at discharge or revocation, civil judgment to be entered.

Minutes:  14CF1450/14TR11356.  Clerk/T. Lehman.  ADA Margaret Drees appeared for the State.  Deft appeared in person w/Atty Kristyne Watson.  Testimony taken from Dr. Collins (via telephone).  Doctor's report entered into evidence.  State rests.  Defense has no witnesses.  Arguments heard.  Court finds the deft is not competent at this time to proceed but is likely to become competent within the time prescribed by law.  Case is suspended at this time; deft is committed to the Dept of Health Services for in-patient treatment not to exceed a period of 12mos.  Medication order shall also be ordered.  KSD shall transport the deft to the facility.  Deft not entitled to any credit.  Case recalled - deft is released to the custody of her parents.  Her parents will reside with the deft until a bed is available at Winnebago.  Upon the availability of a bed, deft's parents shall transport her to the PSB in order for the KSD to transport her to Winnebago.
